# ============================================================
# .gitignore for My ML / AI / Python Projects
# ============================================================
#
# Hi! This file explains which files and folders I do NOT upload to this GitHub repository.
#
# Some files are useful for readers, recruiters, and collaborators.
# Other files are only useful on my own computer, or they may be too large, private, temporary, or automatically generated.
#
# This file helps keep the repository clean, safe, and easy to understand.
#
# Example:
# .env
#
# This means I do not upload a file named .env.
#
# Example:
# *.pyc
#
# The * means "any file name".
# So *.pyc means I do not upload any file ending with .pyc.
#
# Example:
# venv/
#
# The / means it is a folder.
# So venv/ means I do not upload the venv folder.
# ============================================================


# ============================================================
# 1. Python temporary/cache files
# ============================================================
#
# When I run Python code, Python may automatically create temporary
# files and folders.
#
# These files help Python run faster on my computer, but they are not
# my actual project code.
#
# I do not upload them because:
# - they are created automatically
# - they are not useful for readers
# - they can make the repository look messy
#
# My real Python files are the .py files that I write myself.

__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.pyd


# ============================================================
# 2. Python virtual environments
# ============================================================
#
# I use virtual environments to install the packages needed for my projects.
#
# A virtual environment may contain packages like:
# - pandas
# - numpy
# - scikit-learn
# - matplotlib
# - tensorflow
# - torch
#
# These folders can become very large, so I do not upload them.
#
# Instead, I upload requirements.txt when possible.
# That file shows which packages are needed.
#
# Someone else can install the packages by running:
#
# pip install -r requirements.txt
#
# This is cleaner than uploading my whole virtual environment.

venv/
.venv/
env/


# ============================================================
# 3. Jupyter Notebook checkpoint files
# ============================================================
#
# Many of my ML/AI projects may use Jupyter Notebooks.
#
# Jupyter can automatically create backup folders called:
# .ipynb_checkpoints/
#
# I do not upload these checkpoint folders because they are automatic
# backup files, not the main notebook.
#
# The notebook I want people to read is usually something like:
#
# notebook.ipynb
#
# or:
#
# analysis.ipynb

.ipynb_checkpoints/


# ============================================================
# 4. Secret files: passwords, API keys, and private tokens
# ============================================================
#
# Some projects may use private keys or passwords.
#
# For example, a .env file could contain:
#
# OPENAI_API_KEY=my_private_key
# DATABASE_PASSWORD=my_password
# SECRET_KEY=my_secret
#
# I do not upload these files because they may contain private information.
#
# This protects:
# - my API keys
# - passwords
# - database credentials
# - private tokens
#
# Important:
# Public GitHub repositories should never contain secret keys.

.env
.env.local
.env.*


# ============================================================
# 5. Raw or private datasets
# ============================================================
#
# In ML/AI projects, datasets are often stored in a data/ folder.
#
# I may have folders like:
#
# data/raw/
# data/private/
#
# I do not upload these folders because raw datasets can be:
# - very large
# - private
# - copyrighted
# - messy
# - not necessary for understanding the project
#
# Instead, I may upload:
# - a small sample dataset
# - cleaned example data
# - a link to the original dataset
# - instructions in the README
#
# For example, I may upload:
#
# data/sample_data.csv
#
# But I usually avoid uploading full raw datasets.

data/raw/
data/private/


# ============================================================
# 6. Large machine learning model files
# ============================================================
#
# Some ML/AI projects create saved model files after training.
#
# Examples:
#
# model.pkl
# model.joblib
# neural_network.h5
# pytorch_model.pt
# model.pth
# model.onnx
#
# These files can become large, especially for deep learning projects.
#
# I usually do not upload large model files directly to GitHub because
# GitHub is mainly for code, documentation, and project structure.
#
# Instead, I try to upload:
# - the training code
# - the prediction code
# - the evaluation results
# - screenshots or charts
# - instructions for reproducing the model
#
# If a model file is small and important for a demo, I may choose to
# upload it manually by removing that specific rule.

*.pkl
*.joblib
*.h5
*.pt
*.pth
*.onnx


# ============================================================
# 7. Log files
# ============================================================
#
# Some programs create log files while running.
#
# Examples:
#
# training.log
# app.log
# error.log
#
# Logs can be useful on my computer while debugging, but I usually
# do not upload them because:
# - they can be temporary
# - they can become long
# - they may contain private paths or information
#
# If I want to show important training results, I will usually put them
# in the README or in the results/ folder instead.

*.log
logs/


# ============================================================
# 8. Operating system files
# ============================================================
#
# My computer may automatically create hidden system files.
#
# For example:
#
# .DS_Store  -> created by macOS
# Thumbs.db  -> created by Windows
#
# These files are not part of my ML/AI projects.
# They only store local folder display information on my computer.
#
# I do not upload them because they are unnecessary for readers.

.DS_Store
Thumbs.db


# ============================================================
# 9. Code editor settings
# ============================================================
#
# Code editors may create folders for personal settings.
#
# Examples:
#
# .vscode/  -> Visual Studio Code settings
# .idea/    -> PyCharm or IntelliJ settings
#
# I usually do not upload these because they may contain settings that
# are only useful for my own computer.
#
# The project should be understandable without my personal editor setup.

.vscode/
.idea/


# ============================================================
# 10. Experiment output folders
# ============================================================
#
# ML/AI experiments can create many automatic output folders.
#
# Examples:
#
# outputs/
# runs/
# checkpoints/
#
# These folders may contain:
# - temporary experiment outputs
# - model checkpoints
# - generated files
# - repeated training runs
#
# I do not upload them by default because they can become large and messy.
#
# Important:
# I may still upload selected result files that help explain the project,
# such as:
#
# results/confusion_matrix.png
# results/accuracy_chart.png
# results/sample_predictions.png
#
# The goal is to show useful results, not every temporary experiment file.

outputs/
runs/
checkpoints/


# ============================================================
# 11. Temporary backup files
# ============================================================
#
# Sometimes programs or editors create temporary backup files.
#
# Examples:
#
# file.tmp
# file.temp
# old_version.bak
#
# I do not upload these because they are not part of the final project.

*.tmp
*.temp
*.bak


# ============================================================
# 12. Files I usually WANT to upload
# ============================================================
#
# I normally want these files to appear in the repository:
#
# README.md
# requirements.txt
# notebook.ipynb
# src/
# results/
# data/sample_data.csv
#
# These files help people understand:
# - what the project does
# - how to install the requirements
# - how the model works
# - what results I achieved
# - how to run the project
#
# So I do NOT add those files to .gitignore.
# ============================================================
